Executive Summary

Recommendation for blended reporting

  • prepare printable reports, easy-access html summaries, presentations
  • include live-interaction with dashboards
  • combine reporting and computation in a joint environment
  • use templates with corporate design elements
  • do this in an Open Science way with R, RMarkdown and R/Shiny

apply existing visualization technology and bridge reporting from Higher Education Research and Science Studies.

Starting point

Data set I: DZHW Science Survey of 2019
Data set II: EUROSTUDENT VII of 2019-2021

Challenges

  • Finding appropriate visualizations to be included in the Barometer with special regard to understandability for laymen and accessibility for people with disabilities but also as an exploratory source for further data analysis.
  • Comparing visualization solutions, aiming at developing recommendations for software choice and drawing conclusions on dataset requirements.
  • Transferring insights gained from visualizing the Science Survey data to the EUROSTUDENT dataset.

Empirical State of Graphics

  • we have evaluated a poster series (EUROSTUDENT) and a report (DZHW Science Survey) which contain 35 and 38 visualizations

shares of female students (EUROSTUDENT)

satisfaction with work environment (DZHW Science Survey)

state of graphics

  • Bar charts are famous for representations of categorical variables
  • We can improve informativity of bar charts with panelized layouts and the colorblind-friendly DZHW color scheme

The template for reports

  • Clear visualizations with familiar plot types are accessible for laymen.
  • Panelization and stacking allow for visualization of four variables in one bar chart.
  • HTML reports are highly accessible for visually impaired audiences.
  • Alternative texts can easily be added to plots.

However, sometimes we need printable reports with fixed layout.

  • RMarkdown works with the DZHW report template, but manual editing of the Word document is required afterwards.

The reporting guideline

  • Practical display of RMarkdown applied to EUROSTUDENT VII and DZHW Science Survey data sets.
  • e.g.how to write functions for plots:
stacked_bars_cross <- function(data, column1,column2, ...) {...}
  • which can then be applied to different data sets:

The R/Shiny dashboard

  • Dashboards make use of aggregated data sets which can be made openly available
  • we have prepared a proof of concept

Workflow: Blend text production and computation!

  • start an RMarkdown report (see template)
  • write functions for visualizations and apply them to your data set (see guideline)
  • add text and compile an html report
  • share your source code in a FAIR way
  • render your code again as docx to a printable report
  • move your analyses to an RMarkdown presentation and present them at conferences
  • move your functions to an R/Shiny app and have people play with (a part of) your data set (see documentation)
  • and reuse your functions applying them to other data sets

Possible next steps

Near future: Implement report template

  • Incorporate suggestions from todays feedback (Thank you!)
  • Discuss further improvements with the community at DZHW
  • get approval from DZHW
  • distribute with other templates (hopefully)

Distant future: Make a larger step towards Open Science

  • have a common knowledge base at DZHW
  • further develop template(s) as a community
  • collect best-practice examples with shared code in a repository at DZHW
